# Backend Engineering Rules (Node.js + Express + MongoDB)

## 1. Architecture & Structure

- Always follow modular architecture:
  Controller -> Service -> Repository -> Database
- Never place business logic inside controllers
- Each module must be self-contained inside `/modules/<module-name>`

## 2. Controllers

- Controllers must only handle:
  - Request parsing
  - Calling service layer
  - Sending response
- Controllers must NOT:
  - Contain business logic
  - Access database directly
- Keep controllers under 15 lines where possible

## 3. Services (Business Logic Layer)

- All core logic must reside in services
- Services must be reusable and independent of HTTP layer
- Avoid direct use of req/res in services
- Break large logic into smaller helper functions

## 4. Repository Layer

- Repository handles all database queries
- No business logic in repository
- Always abstract DB calls behind repository functions

## 5. Validation

- Validate all incoming data using schema validation (Zod/Joi)
- Reject invalid input before reaching service layer
- Never trust client input

## 6. Error Handling

- Use centralized error handling middleware
- Throw custom errors (e.g., AppError) from services
- Do not use try-catch in every controller
- Always return consistent error responses

## 7. Naming Conventions

- Use clear, descriptive names:
  - createExpense, calculateBalances, optimizeSettlements
- Avoid generic names like handleData, processStuff

## 8. Code Quality

- Use async/await (avoid .then/.catch)
- Keep functions small and focused
- Avoid deeply nested logic
- Use early returns where possible

## 9. Constants & Enums

- Avoid magic strings
- Store constants like split types in a separate file

## 10. Transactions & Data Integrity

- Use database transactions for critical operations:
  - Expense creation
  - Ledger updates
- Ensure atomic operations

## 11. Logging

- Use structured logging (no console.log in production code)
- Log important events (expense creation, errors)

## 12. Security

- Hash passwords using bcrypt
- Use JWT for authentication
- Sanitize inputs
- Implement rate limiting for APIs

## 13. API Response Format

Always return responses in the format:

```json
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {},
  "message": "optional message"
}
```

## 14. Edge Case Handling

Always validate:

- Split totals match amount
- No duplicate participants
- Valid user IDs
- User belongs to group (if group expense)

## 15. Advanced Logic Rules

- Always store normalized splitDetails in expense
- Use ledger-based system for balances
- Settlement optimization must minimize transactions

## 16. Clean Code Practices

- Follow single responsibility principle
- Avoid code duplication
- Extract reusable utilities
- Write readable and maintainable code

## 17. Testing (Optional but Recommended)

- Write unit tests for core logic:
  - Split calculation
  - Settlement optimization

## 18. Documentation

- Add comments only for complex logic
- Keep code self-explanatory
- Maintain clean README

---

## Strict Rule

If any logic is written in the wrong layer (e.g., business logic in controller), refactor it immediately.
